Document: Using SDFGI
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/global_illumination/using_sdfgi.rst
Summary: This document explains how to use Signed Distance Field Global Illumination (SDFGI) in Godot Engine.

SDFGI is a real-time global illumination technique that uses signed distance fields to approximate indirect lighting. It's particularly useful for dynamic scenes where lighting conditions change frequently.

To enable SDFGI, you need to add a SDFGI environment to your scene. This can be done by adding a WorldEnvironment node and creating a new Environment resource for it. In the Environment resource, under the "Global Illumination" section, select "SDFGI" as the Method.

Once SDFGI is enabled, you'll need to configure its parameters. The most important parameters are:

*   **Cascades**: This determines the number of SDFGI cascades used. More cascades provide higher quality but increase performance cost.
*   **Min Cell Size**: This sets the minimum size of the SDFGI grid cells. Smaller cells provide more detail but increase memory usage and computation.
*   **Max Distance**: This defines the maximum distance at which SDFGI will be calculated.
*   **Energy**: This controls the intensity of the indirect lighting.
*   **Bias**: This adjusts the bias of the SDFGI calculation, which can help to reduce artifacts.
*   **Normal Bias**: This adjusts the bias of the normal calculation, which can help to reduce artifacts related to surface normals.
*   **Read Only**: If enabled, SDFGI will not update dynamically. This can improve performance if your scene lighting does not change.

You may also need to adjust the "Occlusion" and "Ambient" settings in the Environment resource to fine-tune the appearance of the global illumination.

For SDFGI to work correctly, your scene geometry needs to be properly set up. Meshes should have appropriate collision shapes, and materials should have reasonable albedo and roughness values.

SDFGI is a powerful tool for achieving realistic lighting in real-time 3D applications. By understanding its parameters and limitations, you can effectively use it to enhance the visual quality of your Godot projects.
---CHUNK---
Document: Using SDFGI
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/global_illumination/using_sdfgi.rst
Summary: Introduces Signed Distance Field Global Illumination (SDFGI) in Godot, explaining its capabilities, limitations, and performance characteristics.
Signed distance field global illumination (SDFGI) is a novel technique available in Godot. It provides semi-real-time global illumination that scales to any world size and works with procedurally generated levels. SDFGI supports dynamic lights, but not dynamic occluders or dynamic emissive surfaces. Therefore, SDFGI provides better real-time ability than baked lightmaps, but worse real-time ability than VoxelGI. From a performance standpoint, SDFGI is one of the most demanding global illumination techniques in Godot. Like with VoxelGI, there are still many settings available to tweak its performance requirements at the cost of quality. Note: SDFGI is only supported when using the Forward+ renderer, not the Mobile or Compatibility renderers. See doc_introduction_to_global_illumination_comparison for a comparison of GI techniques available in Godot 4.
---CHUNK---
